<div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
<!--update translation-->
		
	<p n="1">Prosperity! Fortune!</p>
	
	<p n="1">Twenty seventh year, ninetieth day of Rājakesarin, the king <supplied reason="subaudible">who took</supplied> the head of the heroic Pāṇḍya king, who apportionned pots at Kāntaḷūrccālai <gap reason="ellipsis"/></p>
	
	<p n="1-6">
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
		Arumoḻitēvaccaruppētimaṅkalam
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>who graciously took the Eastern country, the Ganges and Kaṭāram
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
		Vakaiyālaṉ
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
		of the <foreign>veḷḷāṉvakai</foreign> category <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>varicai</foreign></supplied> 
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
		so that it is put in the account, he graciously uttered of his glorious mouth
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/> the (officer in charge of) <foreign>tirumantiravōlai</foreign> Caḷukki-k-kulakāla-mūvēntavēḷāṉ
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
		of the Kṣatra-cikāmaṇi-vaḷanāṭu
		<gap reason="ellipsis"/>
	</p> 
	
      	</div>
      	
<div type="commentary">
	      		
      		<p>
            	<lb n="2"/> Kaṭāram is a port in Southeast Asia. The phrase "who graciously took the Eastern country, the Ganges and Kaṭāram" is formulaic and found in many cōḻa inscriptions.
      		</p>
      			
